{{Use mdy dates|date=June 2023}} {{Use American English|date=June 2023}} {{pp|small=yes}} {{Short description|Political backlash against LGBT people}} {{Infobox civil conflict | title = 2020s anti-LGBT movement in the United States | image = Chaya Raichik and MTG.jpg | date = 2021{{efn|While anti-LGBT sentiment existed before 2021, a notable uptick in anti-LGBT laws, legislation, and protests began in 2021. Notable events include the [[Wi Spa controversy]] and the passing of Arkansas' [[Arkansas House Bill 1570 (2021)|Save Adolescents From Experimentation (SAFE) Act]], one of the first bills prohibiting child transgender healthcare.}} {{ndash}} ongoing | partof = [[Homophobia in the United States|homophobia]], [[transphobia in the United States|transphobia]] and [[LGBT history in the United States|LGBT history]] in the United States | place = United States | caption = U.S. representative [[Marjorie Taylor Greene]] of Georgia and [[Libs of TikTok]] creator [[Chaya Raichik]] holding a sign in March 2023 stating that there are only two [[gender]]s. | causes = Increasing transparency, relevance, and acceptance of [[LGBT]] identity in the United States | goals = To reverse social change in relation to [[LGBT rights]] in the United States | methods = * Laws restricting LGBT rights: ** [[Bathroom bill|Transgender bathroom use restrictions]] ** Bans and restrictions on [[Transgender health care|gender-affirming care]] (especially for [[Transgender youth|minors]]) ** [[Anti-LGBT curriculum laws in the United States|Anti-LGBT curriculum laws]] ** Attempted [[Drag panic|restrictions on drag performances for children]] ** Prohibitions of [[transgender people in sports]] * [[2021–2023 book banning in the United States|Book bans of LGBT content]] * Harassment of hospitals providing gender-affirming care * [[Boycott]]s against companies promoting LGBT products * [[LGBT grooming conspiracy theory|Conspiracy theories around grooming]] | status = Ongoing }}
The '''2020s anti-LGBT movement in the United States''' is an ongoing [[Backlash (sociology)|political backlash]] from [[Social conservatism|social conservatives]] against [[LGBT community|LGBT people]]. It has included [[Legislature|legislative]] proposals of [[Bathroom bill|bathroom use restrictions]], [[Transgender rights in the United States|bans on gender-affirming care]], [[Anti-LGBT curriculum laws in the United States|anti-LGBT curriculum laws]], [[Drag panic|laws against drag performance]]s, [[2021–2023 book banning in the United States|book bans]], [[boycott]]s, and [[LGBT grooming conspiracy theory|conspiracy theories around grooming]].<ref>{{cite news |title=America's far right is increasingly protesting against LGBT people |url=https://www.economist.com/graphic-detail/2023/01/13/americas-far-right-is-increasingly-protesting-against-lgbt-people |newspaper=The Economist |access-date=May 24, 2023 |archive-date=May 24, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230524065520/https://www.economist.com/graphic-detail/2023/01/13/americas-far-right-is-increasingly-protesting-against-lgbt-people |url-status=live }}</ref> Between 2018 and 2023, hundreds of anti-LGBT laws were considered, with more than one hundred passed into law.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Miller |first1=Susan |title='War' on LGBTQ existence: 8 ways the record onslaught of 650 bills targets the community |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/nation/2023/03/31/650-anti-lgbtq-bills-introduced-us/11552357002/ |website=USA Today |access-date=17 July 2023 |archive-date=July 17, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230717153641/https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/nation/2023/03/31/650-anti-lgbtq-bills-introduced-us/11552357002/ |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Rogers |first1=Kaleigh |last2=Radcliffe |first2=Mary |title=Over 100 Anti-LGBTQ+ Laws Passed In The Last Five Years — Half Of Them This Year |url=https://fivethirtyeight.com/features/anti-lgbtq-laws-red-states/ |website=FiveThirtyEight |date=May 25, 2023 |access-date=17 July 2023 |archive-date=May 25, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230525195300/https://fivethirtyeight.com/features/anti-lgbtq-laws-red-states/ |url-status=live }}</ref>
The backlash has been widely considered a [[moral panic]]<ref>{{cite web |last1=Rozsa |first1=Matthew |title=Why the moral panic over "grooming" is so effective at manipulating the right-wing mind Experts explain the history of the right creating false narratives that connect LGBTQ issues to pedophilia |url=https://www.salon.com/2023/01/30/why-the-moral-panic-over-grooming-is-so-effective-at-manipulating-the-right-wing-mind/ |website=Salon |date=January 30, 2023 |access-date=21 July 2023 |archive-date=July 21, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230721085310/https://www.salon.com/2023/01/30/why-the-moral-panic-over-grooming-is-so-effective-at-manipulating-the-right-wing-mind/ |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine |last1=Morrish |first1=Lydia |title=The US Is Exporting Anti-LGBTQ Hate Online |url=https://www.wired.com/story/the-us-is-exporting-anti-lgbtq-hate-online/ |magazine=Wired |access-date=21 July 2023}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Romana |first1=Aja |title=The right's moral panic over "grooming" invokes age-old homophobia "Groomer" accusations against liberals and the LGBTQ community are recycled Satanic Panic. |url=https://www.vox.com/culture/23025505/leftist-groomers-homophobia-satanic-panic-explained |website=Vox |date=April 21, 2022 |access-date=21 July 2023 |archive-date=May 17, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230517125930/https://www.vox.com/culture/23025505/leftist-groomers-homophobia-satanic-panic-explained |url-status=live }}</ref> and part of a larger [[culture war]] in the United States.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Drenon |first1=Brandon |title=Celebrating Pride in the midst of a culture war |work=BBC News |date=July 5, 2023 |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-66101220 |access-date=21 July 2023 |archive-date=July 21, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230721010158/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-66101220 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Culture War, Redux |work=The New York Times |date=April 8, 2022 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2022/04/08/briefing/culture-war-lgbt-rights-us-politics.html |access-date=21 July 2023 |last1=Leonhardt |first1=David |last2=Philbrick |first2=Ian Prasad |archive-date=July 21, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230721010158/https://www.nytimes.com/2022/04/08/briefing/culture-war-lgbt-rights-us-politics.html |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Eugenios |first1=Jillien |title=How 1970s Christian crusader Anita Bryant helped spawn Florida's LGBTQ culture war |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/nbc-out/out-news/1970s-christian-crusader-anita-bryant-helped-spawn-floridas-lgbtq-cult-rcna24215 |website=NBC News |date=April 14, 2022 |access-date=21 July 2023 |archive-date=July 24, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230724231041/https://www.nbcnews.com/nbc-out/out-news/1970s-christian-crusader-anita-bryant-helped-spawn-floridas-lgbtq-cult-rcna24215 |url-status=live }}</ref> Scholars have cited rising anti-LGBT attitudes and policies as an example of [[democratic backsliding in the United States|democratic backsliding]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://williamsinstitute.law.ucla.edu/publications/anti-lgbt-politics-democracy/|title=What Anti-LGBT Politics in the U.S. Means for Democracy at Home and Abroad|website=Williams Institute|access-date=June 19, 2023|archive-date=June 13, 2023|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230613210124/https://williamsinstitute.law.ucla.edu/publications/anti-lgbt-politics-democracy/|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hrw.org/news/2022/09/06/how-targeting-lgbtq-rights-are-part-authoritarian-playbook|title=How Targeting LGBTQ+ Rights Are Part of the Authoritarian Playbook|date=September 6, 2022|access-date=June 19, 2023|archive-date=June 13, 2023|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230613210116/https://www.hrw.org/news/2022/09/06/how-targeting-lgbtq-rights-are-part-authoritarian-playbook|url-status=live}}</ref> The backlash has been connected to similar conservative backlashes in [[Hungarian anti-LGBT law|Hungary]], [[Russian gay propaganda law|Russia]], and the [[LGBT rights in the Middle East|Middle East]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Tharoor |first1=Ishaan |title=The Orbanization of America: Florida shadows Hungary's war on LGBTQ rights |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/2022/05/18/cpac-hungary-lgbtq-orban-florida-desantis/ |newspaper=The Washington Post |access-date=29 August 2023}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Albarracín-Caballero |first1=Mauricio |title=How Targeting LGBTQ+ Rights Are Part of the Authoritarian Playbook |url=https://www.hrw.org/news/2022/09/06/how-targeting-lgbtq-rights-are-part-authoritarian-playbook |website=Human Rights Watch |date=September 6, 2022 |access-date=29 August 2023}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=El Chamaa |first1=Mohamad |title=Anti-LGBTQ backlash grows across Middle East, echoing U.S. culture wars |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/2023/08/03/middle-east-lgbtq-gay-transgender/ |newspaper=The Washington Post |access-date=29 August 2023}}</ref> ==Grooming conspiracy theory== {{main|LGBT grooming conspiracy theory}}{{LGBT sidebar|history}}
Members of the far-right and a number of mainstream [[Conservatism|conservatives]], mostly in the United States, have used the term "groomer" to falsely accuse LGBT people, as well as their allies and progressives in general, of systematically using LGBT sex education and campaigns for LGBT rights as a method of [[child grooming]] and enabling [[pedophilia]]. Usage of this term increased in the 2020s.{{Citation needed|date=October 2023}}
In the United States, the popularization of the term has been linked to [[Christopher Rufo]], who tweeted about "winning the language war", and [[James A. Lindsay]] in August 2021.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/outlook/2022/04/05/qanon-groomer-hawley-desantis-jackson/ |title=The QAnon catchphrases that took over the Jackson hearings |date=April 7, 2022 |orig-date=April 5, 2022 |author1=Donald Moynihan |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] |place=Washington, D.C. |issn=0190-8286 |oclc=1330888409 |access-date=May 24, 2023 |archive-date=April 10, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230410145445/https://www.washingtonpost.com/outlook/2022/04/05/qanon-groomer-hawley-desantis-jackson/ |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |date= April 27, 2022 |title= How the Intellectual Dark Web Spawned 'Groomer' Panic |work= The Daily Beast |url= https://www.thedailybeast.com/how-the-intellectual-dark-web-spawned-anti-lgbtq-groomer-panic |access-date= May 16, 2022 |archive-date= May 16, 2022 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20220516083524/https://www.thedailybeast.com/how-the-intellectual-dark-web-spawned-anti-lgbtq-groomer-panic |url-status= live }}</ref> Following the [[Wi Spa controversy]]&nbsp;in July 2021, [[Julia Serano]] noted a rise in false accusations of grooming directed towards transgender people, saying that it appeared as if there was a movement to "lay the foundation for just smearing all trans people as child sexual predators".<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2021/jul/28/anti-trans-video-los-angeles-protest-wi-spa | title='A nightmare scenario': How an anti-trans Instagram post led to violence in the streets | website=[[TheGuardian.com]] | date=July 28, 2021 | access-date=May 24, 2023 | archive-date=January 4, 2022 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220104121718/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2021/jul/28/anti-trans-video-los-angeles-protest-wi-spa | url-status=live }}</ref> [[Libs of TikTok]] (LoTT) also slurs LGBT people, supporters of LGBT youth,<ref name="Slate">{{cite web |last1=Stahl |first1=Jeremy |title=The Hate-Fueled and Hugely Influential World of Libs of TikTok |url=https://slate.com/news-and-politics/2022/04/chaya-raichik-libs-tiktok-groomer-tweets.html |website=Slate Magazine |access-date=July 27, 2022 |language=en |date=April 27, 2022 |archive-date=July 27, 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220727081413/https://slate.com/news-and-politics/2022/04/chaya-raichik-libs-tiktok-groomer-tweets.html |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Persaud |first1=Chris |title=Babylon Bee CEO of Juno Beach backs Twitter firebrand who calls LGBTQ people pedophiles |url=https://www.palmbeachpost.com/story/news/local/2022/05/10/babylon-bee-ceo-juno-beach-backs-libs-tiktok-creator/7385009001/ |website=The Palm Beach Post |access-date=July 27, 2022 |archive-date=May 16, 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220516050225/https://www.palmbeachpost.com/story/news/local/2022/05/10/babylon-bee-ceo-juno-beach-backs-libs-tiktok-creator/7385009001/ |url-status=live }}</ref> and those who teach about sexuality as "groomers."<ref>{{cite web |title=The Twitter activist behind the far-right 'Libs of TikTok' is an Orthodox Jew. Does that matter? |url=https://www.jta.org/2022/04/19/politics/the-twitter-activist-behind-the-far-right-libs-of-tiktok-is-an-orthodox-jew-does-that-matter |website=Jewish Telegraphic Agency |access-date=July 27, 2022 |date=April 19, 2022 |archive-date=July 15, 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220715045148/https://www.jta.org/2022/04/19/politics/the-twitter-activist-behind-the-far-right-libs-of-tiktok-is-an-orthodox-jew-does-that-matter |url-status=live }}</ref> In 2021, LoTT made false claims that the [[Trevor Project]] was a "grooming organization" and that [[Chasten Buttigieg]] was "grooming kids".<ref name="Slate" /> LoTT creator Chaya Raichik said on the ''[[Tucker Carlson Today]]'' show that LGBT people "Want to groom kids. They're recruiting."<ref>{{Cite web |last=Levesque |first=Brody |date=December 28, 2022 |title=Libs of TikTok tells Tucker Carlson: LGBTQ+ are a poisonous cult |url=https://www.losangelesblade.com/2022/12/27/libs-of-tiktok-tells-tucker-carlson-lgbtq-are-a-poisonous-cult/ |access-date=February 12, 2023 |website=[[Los Angeles Blade]] |language=en-US |archive-date=February 12, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230212145559/https://www.losangelesblade.com/2022/12/27/libs-of-tiktok-tells-tucker-carlson-lgbtq-are-a-poisonous-cult/ |url-status=live }}</ref>
[[File:Libs of TikTok logo.jpg|thumb|Far-right anti-LGBT Twitter account [[Libs of TikTok]] (logo pictured) uses the term "groomers" as a pejorative for [[LGBT]] people.|left|200x200px]]
The conspiracy theory then moved into the American conservative mainstream, with a number of high-profile cases of its use in Spring 2022, including its use by members of the [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican Party]].<ref name= Vox>{{cite web |last1=Romano |first1=Aja |title=The right's moral panic over "grooming" invokes age-old homophobia |url=https://www.vox.com/culture/23025505/leftist-groomers-homophobia-satanic-panic-explained |website=[[Vox (website)|Vox]] |date=April 21, 2022 |publisher=[[Vox Media]] |access-date=July 28, 2022 |archive-date=May 17, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230517125930/https://www.vox.com/culture/23025505/leftist-groomers-homophobia-satanic-panic-explained |url-status=live }}</ref> On February 24, the right-wing [[The Heritage Foundation]] issued a tweet stating that the [[Florida Parental Rights in Education Act]] "protects young children from sexual grooming".<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://slate.com/news-and-politics/2022/04/christina-pushaw-ron-desantis-libsoftiktok-groomer.html |title=How One Florida Woman With Twitter Problems Plunged Us Into a Nightmarish National Conversation About "Grooming" |last1=Mathis-Lilley |first1=Ben |date=April 21, 2022 |work=[[Slate (magazine)|Slate]] |access-date=May 24, 2023 |archive-date=May 28, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230528043711/https://slate.com/news-and-politics/2022/04/christina-pushaw-ron-desantis-libsoftiktok-groomer.html |url-status=live }}</ref> During the debate over the act, [[Christina Pushaw]], press secretary to the state's governor [[Ron DeSantis]], tweeted that anyone who opposes the act was "probably a groomer". In April 2022, [[Marjorie Taylor Greene]] referred to the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic Party]] as "the party of killing babies, grooming and transitioning children, and pro-pedophile politics". Also that month, a group of [[Radical right (United States)|far-right]] extremists and conspiracy theorists held a demonstration at [[Disney World]] in which they accused Disney of grooming.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Alfonseca |first1=Kiara |title=Some Republicans use false 'pedophilia' claims to attack Democrats, LGBTQ people |url=https://abcnews.go.com/US/republicans-false-pedophilia-claims-attack-democrats-lgbtq-people/story?id=84344687 |website=abcnews.go.com |publisher=ABC News |access-date=July 28, 2022 |archive-date=February 13, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230213101039/https://abcnews.go.com/US/republicans-false-pedophilia-claims-attack-democrats-lgbtq-people/story?id=84344687 |url-status=live }}</ref> Disney has been the focus of several other uses of the conspiracy – [[Jim Banks]] and 19 other members of the [[Republican Study Committee]] published a letter to Disney accusing the corporation of "purposefully influencing small children with its political and sexual agenda".<ref name="Brooks April2022"/>
Since then, numerous right wing pundits have described the behavior of parents and teachers who support minors in their transgender identities as grooming, and the term "groomer" has widely been used by conservative media and politicians who want to denounce the LGBT community and its allies by implying that they are pedophiles or pedophile-enablers.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.vox.com/platform/amp/culture/23025505/leftist-groomers-homophobia-satanic-panic-explained |title=The right's moral panic over 'grooming' invokes age-old homophobia |last1=Romano |first1=Aja |date=April 21, 2022 |work=[[Vox (website)|Vox]] |access-date=May 24, 2023 |archive-date=April 25, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230425100822/https://www.vox.com/platform/amp/culture/23025505/leftist-groomers-homophobia-satanic-panic-explained |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.vice.com/amp/en/article/g5q9vx/child-grooming-lgbtq-smear |title=Conservatives Are Smearing 'Don't Say Gay' Opponents as Pedophile 'Groomers' |last1=Cameron |first1=Joseph |work=[[Vice (magazine)|Vice]] |date=April 5, 2022 |access-date=May 24, 2023 |archive-date=January 8, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230108090000/https://www.vice.com/amp/en/article/g5q9vx/child-grooming-lgbtq-smear |url-status=live }}</ref> ''[[Slate Magazine]]'' later described the word "grooming" as "the buzzword of the season".<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://slate.com/news-and-politics/2022/04/christina-pushaw-ron-desantis-libsoftiktok-groomer.html |title=How One Florida Woman With Twitter Problems Plunged Us Into a Nightmarish National Conversation About "Grooming" |last1=Mathis-Lilley |first1=Ben |date=April 21, 2022 |work=[[Slate Magazine]] |access-date=May 24, 2023 |archive-date=May 28, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230528043711/https://slate.com/news-and-politics/2022/04/christina-pushaw-ron-desantis-libsoftiktok-groomer.html |url-status=live }}</ref> In March 2022, Fox News host [[Laura Ingraham]] claimed that schools were becoming "grooming centers for gender identity radicals", dedicating an entire segment of her show to the topic a couple of weeks later.<ref name="Brooks April2022">{{cite web | url=https://thehill.com/homenews/house/3262988-groomer-debate-inflames-gop-fight-over-florida-law/ | title='Groomer' debate inflames GOP fight over Florida law | date=April 8, 2022 | work=[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]] | access-date=May 24, 2023 | archive-date=April 1, 2023 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230401050441/https://thehill.com/homenews/house/3262988-groomer-debate-inflames-gop-fight-over-florida-law/ | url-status=live }}</ref> In April 2022, the left-leaning media watchdog [[Media Matters]] published a study stating that within a three-week period spanning from March 17 to April 6, [[Fox News]] ran 170 segments on trans people, throughout which the network "repeatedly invoked the long-debunked myth that trans people pose a threat to minors and seek to groom them".<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.mediamatters.org/fox-news/doom-groom-fox-news-has-aired-170-segments-discussing-trans-people-past-three-weeks |title="Doom & Groom": Fox News has aired 170 segments discussing trans people in the past three weeks |last1=Paterson |first1=Alex |website=[[Media Matters for America]] |date=April 8, 2022 |access-date=May 24, 2023 |archive-date=June 1, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230601182823/https://www.mediamatters.org/fox-news/doom-groom-fox-news-has-aired-170-segments-discussing-trans-people-past-three-weeks |url-status=live }}</ref>
==Education==
=== Anti-LGBT curriculum laws === [[File:Student protest Palm Harbor FL.jpg|thumb|right|A student protest at [[Palm Harbor University High School]] against the [[Florida Parental Rights in Education Act]].]] {{main|Anti-LGBT curriculum laws in the United States}} {{further|Censorship of school curricula in the United States}} In July 2022, a wave of anti-LGBT curriculum resurgence saw ten such laws beginning to take effect in six different states. Some states enacting these new laws appear to have mirrored similar laws from other states.<ref name="Washington Post">{{Cite news |title=10 anti-LGBTQ laws just went into effect. They all target schools. |language=en-US |newspaper=Washington Post |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/nation/2022/07/08/anti-lgbtq-education-laws-in-effect/ |access-date=July 8, 2022 |issn=0190-8286 |archive-date=July 9, 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220709171121/https://www.washingtonpost.com/nation/2022/07/08/anti-lgbtq-education-laws-in-effect/ |url-status=live }}</ref>
In [[Florida]], the [[Florida Parental Rights in Education Act|Parental Rights in Education law]] and [[Florida Board of Education]] policy bans education on "sexual orientation" or "gender identity" unless it is mandated under state academic standards or as part of an optional reproductive health course or lesson.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Diaz |first=Jaclyn |date=March 28, 2022 |title=Florida's governor signs controversial law opponents dubbed 'Don't Say Gay' |url=https://www.npr.org/2022/03/28/1089221657/dont-say-gay-florida-desantis |access-date=May 11, 2022 |website=[[NPR]] |archive-date=April 26, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230426031531/https://www.npr.org/2022/03/28/1089221657/dont-say-gay-florida-desantis |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Izaguirre |first=Anthony |date=April 19, 2023 |title=Florida board passes DeSantis' expansion of 'Don't Say Gay' |url=https://www.sfgate.com/entertainment/article/florida-board-passes-desantis-expansion-of-17906315.php |access-date=April 19, 2023 |website=SFGATE |language=en-US |archive-date=April 19, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230419162624/https://www.sfgate.com/entertainment/article/florida-board-passes-desantis-expansion-of-17906315.php |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=So-called 'Don't Say Gay' rules expanded through 12th grade in Florida |url=https://abcnews.go.com/Politics/called-dont-gay-rules-expanded-12th-grade-florida/story?id=98691183 |access-date=April 19, 2023 |website=ABC News |language=en |archive-date=April 19, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230419162917/https://abcnews.go.com/Politics/called-dont-gay-rules-expanded-12th-grade-florida/story?id=98691183 |url-status=live }}</ref> In August 2023, the state of Florida dropped [[AP Psychology]] as a course offering, due to a required section on sexual orientation and gender identity.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Meckler |first1=Laura |title=Florida schools drop AP Psychology after state says it violates the law |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/education/2023/08/09/florida-schools-drop-ap-psychology-class/ |newspaper=The Washington Post |access-date=9 August 2023 |archive-date=August 11, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230811070808/https://www.washingtonpost.com/education/2023/08/09/florida-schools-drop-ap-psychology-class/ |url-status=live }}</ref> The same month, [[Tampa]]-area schools announced they would restrict teaching of the works of [[Shakespeare]] in order to comply with the Parental Rights in Education law.<ref>{{cite web |title=Shakespeare and penguin book get caught in Florida's 'Don't Say Gay' laws |url=https://www.npr.org/2023/08/08/1192767641/shakespeare-florida-excerpts-dont-say-gay |website=NPR |access-date=9 August 2023 |archive-date=August 9, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230809195652/https://www.npr.org/2023/08/08/1192767641/shakespeare-florida-excerpts-dont-say-gay |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Pengelly |first1=Martha |title=Florida schools plan to use only excerpts from Shakespeare to avoid 'raunchiness' |url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2023/aug/08/florida-schools-shakespeare-sexual-material |website=The Guardian |date=August 8, 2023 |access-date=9 August 2023 |archive-date=August 9, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230809214320/https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2023/aug/08/florida-schools-shakespeare-sexual-material |url-status=live }}</ref>
Alabama bans the topics for kindergarten to grade 5, except for instruction deemed "age or developmentally appropriate".<ref>{{Cite web |title=Alabama governor signs 'Don't Say Gay,' trans care and bathroom ban bills |url=https://abcnews.go.com/US/alabama-legislature-passes-dont-gay-trans-care-bathroom/story?id=83940764 |access-date=July 1, 2022 |website=ABC News |language=en |archive-date=July 1, 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220701174620/https://abcnews.go.com/US/alabama-legislature-passes-dont-gay-trans-care-bathroom/story?id=83940764 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Holmes |first=Jacob |date=September 9, 2022 |title=Alabama Board of Education codifies "Don't Say Gay" law |url=https://www.alreporter.com/2022/09/09/alabama-board-of-education-codifies-dont-say-gay-law/ |access-date=April 19, 2023 |website=Alabama Political Reporter |language=en-US |archive-date=December 12, 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221212215431/https://www.alreporter.com/2022/09/09/alabama-board-of-education-codifies-dont-say-gay-law/ |url-status=live }}</ref> Five other states ([[Montana]], [[Arizona]], [[Arkansas]], [[Tennessee]] and Florida) require parental notification of instruction on LGBTQ issues and allows parents to opt-out of such instruction.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Movement Advancement Project {{!}} |url=https://www.lgbtmap.org/equality-maps/curricular_laws |access-date=July 1, 2022 |website=www.lgbtmap.org |language=en |archive-date=July 26, 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220726075709/https://www.lgbtmap.org/equality-maps/curricular_laws |url-status=live }}</ref>
In [[California]]—where [[LGBT rights in California#Educational inclusion|state law]] requires students learn about the "role and contributions" of LGBT people in history—multiple protests against the inclusion of LGBT-friendly curriculum resulted in violence.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Blume |first1=Howard |title=What California law requires in teaching about LGBTQ people in public schools |url=https://www.latimes.com/california/story/2022-05-11/california-takes-opposite-path-of-florida-texas-on-inclusive-education |website=Los Angeles Times |date=May 11, 2022 |access-date=June 7, 2023 |archive-date=June 10, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230610094651/https://www.latimes.com/california/story/2022-05-11/california-takes-opposite-path-of-florida-texas-on-inclusive-education |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Lin |first1=Summer |title=Fight erupts at anti-Pride Day protest outside L.A. school where trans teacher's flag was burned |url=https://www.latimes.com/california/story/2023-06-02/parents-protest-lgbtq-pride-day-los-angeles-saticoy-elementary-school |website=Los Angeles Times |date=June 2, 2023 |access-date=June 7, 2023 |archive-date=June 6, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230606192153/https://www.latimes.com/california/story/2023-06-02/parents-protest-lgbtq-pride-day-los-angeles-saticoy-elementary-school |url-status=live }}</ref> At a June 2023 protest in [[Glendale, California|Glendale]], individuals seen protesting LGBTQ curriculum were identified as members of [[hate groups]], such as the [[Proud Boys]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Bella |first1=Timothy |title=Protesters brawl over LGBTQ curriculum outside Calif. school board meeting |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/nation/2023/06/07/california-glendale-school-board-brawl-lgbtq-pride/ |newspaper=Washington Post |access-date=June 7, 2023}}</ref>
Local K-12 school boards across the country adopted a variety of policies regarding trans students, ranging from allowing fully equal rights and non-discrimination for trans students, to requiring trans students to submit to a criminal background check to be allowed to use the bathroom consistent with their gender identity, to implementing full bans on expressing one's self-declared gender at all, including bans on chosen pronouns and pride flags, to even bans on mentioning the very existence of trans people.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://iowatorch.com/2022/04/29/linn-mar-school-board-approves-controversial-transgender-policy/ |title=Linn-Mar School Board approves controversial transgender policy |last1=Vander Hart |first1=Shane |access-date=July 13, 2023 |archive-date=June 8, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230608092226/https://iowatorch.com/2022/04/29/linn-mar-school-board-approves-controversial-transgender-policy/ |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.wtvr.com/news/local-news/hanover-county-proposed-transgender-bathroom-lockerroom-policy-august-9-2022 |last1=Marshall |first1=Maggi |title=Parents, guardians had a lot to say about Hanover's proposed transgender bathroom policy |date=August 10, 2022 |access-date=July 13, 2023 |archive-date=April 6, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230406021448/https://www.wtvr.com/news/local-news/hanover-county-proposed-transgender-bathroom-lockerroom-policy-august-9-2022 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.advocate.com/news/2022/8/01/wisconsin-school-district-bans-preferred-pronouns-pride-symbols |last1=Wiggins |first1=Christopher |title=Wisconsin School District Bans Preferred Pronouns & Pride Symbols |date=August 2022 |access-date=July 13, 2023 |archive-date=April 6, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230406023048/https://www.advocate.com/news/2022/8/01/wisconsin-school-district-bans-preferred-pronouns-pride-symbols |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.texasobserver.org/gcisd-grapevine-coleyville-lgbtq-trans/ |last1=Monacelli |first1=Steven |title='Don't Say Trans' Policy Passes in North Texas School District |date=August 23, 2022 |access-date=July 13, 2023 |archive-date=May 9, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230509142756/https://www.texasobserver.org/gcisd-grapevine-coleyville-lgbtq-trans/ |url-status=live }}</ref> State and local officials in the South used indecency and obscenity laws to ban books from school libraries.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Sasani |first1=Ava |title=‘Archaic’: the Tennessee town that made homosexuality illegal |url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2023/nov/26/tennessee-homosexuality-lgbtq-book-bans-florida |website=The Guardian |access-date=28 November 2023}}</ref>
=== Rollback of discrimination protections === In June 2021, the [[Presidency of Joe Biden|Biden administration]] reinforced that Title IX protected LGBT students from discrimination by including sexual orientation and gender identity in its list of protections.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Cole |first=Chandelis Duster,Devan |date=2021-06-16 |title=Education Department says Title IX protections apply to LGBTQ students {{!}} CNN Politics |url=https://www.cnn.com/2021/06/16/politics/title-ix-lgbtq-students/index.html |access-date=2023-08-05 |website=CNN |language=en |archive-date=August 5, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230805084041/https://www.cnn.com/2021/06/16/politics/title-ix-lgbtq-students/index.html |url-status=live }}</ref>
In August 2021, Tennessee and nineteen other states sued the Department of Education in ''Tennessee v. Department of Education'', alleging that the new Title IX governance constitutes government overreach.<ref>{{Cite web |date=2022-12-22 |title=Attorney General Bonta Urges Appellate Court to Reject Attack on Federal LGBT Anti-Discrimination Protections |url=https://oag.ca.gov/news/press-releases/attorney-general-bonta-urges-appellate-court-reject-attack-federal-lgbt-anti |access-date=2023-08-05 |website=State of California - Department of Justice - Office of the Attorney General |language=en |archive-date=August 5, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230805084048/https://oag.ca.gov/news/press-releases/attorney-general-bonta-urges-appellate-court-reject-attack-federal-lgbt-anti |url-status=live }}</ref> A preliminary injunction was granted by a Tennessee judge in July 2022, blocking enforcement of the new guidance.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Quilantan |first=Bianca |date=2022-07-16 |title=Federal judge blocks Education Department's Title IX guidance that protects transgender students |url=https://www.politico.com/news/2022/07/16/education-departments-title-ix-guidance-transgender-students-00046209 |access-date=2023-08-05 |website=POLITICO |language=en |archive-date=August 5, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230805084045/https://www.politico.com/news/2022/07/16/education-departments-title-ix-guidance-transgender-students-00046209 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Brink |first=Meghan |title=Federal Judge Blocks Title IX Guidance on Transgender Students |url=https://www.insidehighered.com/news/2022/07/19/federal-judge-blocks-ed-dept-title-ix-guidance-trans-students |access-date=2023-08-05 |website=Inside Higher Ed |language=en |archive-date=August 5, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230805084045/https://www.insidehighered.com/news/2022/07/19/federal-judge-blocks-ed-dept-title-ix-guidance-trans-students |url-status=live }}</ref> In December 2022, the Department of Education appealed the decision, which is still pending.<ref>{{Cite web |title=TN Attorney General's Office Responds to Federal Government Appeal of Preliminary Injunction of Title IX Overreach |url=https://www.tn.gov/attorneygeneral/news/2023/1/26/pr23-05.html |access-date=2023-08-05 |website=www.tn.gov |language=en |archive-date=August 5, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230805084046/https://www.tn.gov/attorneygeneral/news/2023/1/26/pr23-05.html |url-status=live }}</ref>
The new guidance was rejected by the [[Florida Department of Education]], calling the guidance a "sexual ideology" that risks the "health, safety, and welfare of Florida students".<ref>{{Cite web |last=Atterbury |first=Andrew |date=2022-07-28 |title=Florida warns schools against following Biden's LGBTQ student protections |url=https://www.politico.com/news/2022/07/28/florida-schools-disregard-federal-title-ix-guidance-00048505 |access-date=2023-08-05 |website=POLITICO |language=en |archive-date=August 4, 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220804062518/https://www.politico.com/news/2022/07/28/florida-schools-disregard-federal-title-ix-guidance-00048505 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Migdon |first=Brooke |date=2022-07-28 |title=Florida DOE to schools: follow Biden transgender protections and risk breaking state law |url=https://thehill.com/changing-america/respect/equality/3578829-florida-doe-to-schools-follow-biden-transgender-protections-and-risk-breaking-state-law/ |access-date=2023-08-05 |website=The Hill |language=en-US |archive-date=August 5, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230805084042/https://thehill.com/changing-america/respect/equality/3578829-florida-doe-to-schools-follow-biden-transgender-protections-and-risk-breaking-state-law/ |url-status=live }}</ref>
==Anti-trans laws== ===Gender transition=== [[File:Students Protest Anti-Trans Law (51934611549).jpg|thumb|Students in [[Des Moines, Iowa|Des Moines]] protesting an anti-trans law signed by Republican Governor [[Kim Reynolds]] in 2022.]] As many as 13 U.S. states banned [[Transgender health care|gender affirming health care]] for [[transgender youth]] in the early-2020s.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Paris |first1=Francesca |title=Bans on Transition Care for Young People Spread Across U.S. |work=The New York Times |date=April 15, 2023 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2023/04/15/upshot/bans-transgender-teenagers.html#:~:text=Ten%20states%20in%20the%20past,surgery%20for%20people%20under%2018. |access-date=May 24, 2023 |archive-date=May 24, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230524053546/https://www.nytimes.com/2023/04/15/upshot/bans-transgender-teenagers.html#:~:text=Ten%20states%20in%20the%20past,surgery%20for%20people%20under%2018. |url-status=live }}</ref>
==== Treatment for adults ==== These states make it easy for trans adults to sue their doctors:
*[[Utah]]: In January 2023, Utah stripped liability protections from any doctor who treats a trans person under the age of 25, and allowing any trans person under 25 to retroactively "disaffirm" consent and sue the doctor for providing care they had at the time consented to.<ref name="sltrib.com" /><ref name="deseret.com" /><ref name="legiscan.com" /><ref name="Schott" /> *[[South Dakota]]: In February 2023, South Dakota passed a similar law as Utah's, but without any age limit.<ref name=":0b">{{Cite web |website=South Dakota Legislature |date=2023 |title=House Bill 1080 |url=https://mylrc.sdlegislature.gov/api/Documents/249156.pdf |access-date=February 14, 2023 |archive-date=February 14, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230214042407/https://mylrc.sdlegislature.gov/api/Documents/249156.pdf |url-status=live }}</ref> *[[LGBT rights in Arkansas|Arkansas]]: On March 13, 2023, Governor [[Sarah Huckabee Sanders]] signed a bill giving adults 15 years to file malpractice lawsuits for gender-affirming care they received as minors, whereas for other types of care (under preexisting law) a malpractice lawsuit must generally be filed within two years.<ref>{{Cite web |date=March 14, 2023 |title=Sarah Huckabee Sanders Signs Arkansas Trans Care Malpractice Bill Into Law |url=https://www.huffpost.com/entry/sarah-huckabee-sanders-arkansas-transgender-health-bill_n_6410f966e4b0cfde25c1c240 |access-date=March 15, 2023 |website=HuffPost |language=en |archive-date=March 14, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230314234618/https://www.huffpost.com/entry/sarah-huckabee-sanders-arkansas-transgender-health-bill_n_6410f966e4b0cfde25c1c240 |url-status=live }}</ref>
These states restrict treatment for trans adults (as well as younger people):
*[[Florida]]: In August 2022, the state of Florida voted to require any trans adult seeking gender affirming healthcare to receive approval from the Florida Board of Medicine at least 24 hours in advance.<ref name="independent.co.uk">{{Cite web |last1=Woodward |first1=Alex |date=August 5, 2022 |title=Florida begins rule-changing process to ban gender-affirming care for trans youth |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/americas/us-politics/florida-transgender-health-ban-desantis-b2139308.html |website=[[Independent.co.uk]] |access-date=May 24, 2023 |archive-date=April 7, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230407070510/https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/americas/us-politics/florida-transgender-health-ban-desantis-b2139308.html |url-status=live }}</ref> On May 17, 2023, DeSantis signed a law<ref>{{Cite web |last=Yurcaba |first=Jo |date=May 17, 2023 |title=DeSantis signs 'Don't Say Gay' expansion, gender-affirming care ban |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/nbc-out/out-politics-and-policy/desantis-signs-dont-say-gay-expansion-gender-affirming-care-ban-rcna84698 |access-date=May 17, 2023 |website=NBC News |language=en |archive-date=May 17, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230517170023/https://www.nbcnews.com/nbc-out/out-politics-and-policy/desantis-signs-dont-say-gay-expansion-gender-affirming-care-ban-rcna84698 |url-status=live }}</ref> banning insurance providers from covering gender-affirming care for adults, as well as banning nurse practitioners and physicians' assistants (estimated to make up 80% of gender affirming care providers) from administering it, and banning it from being offered via telehealth. The Florida state legislature had passed the bill the previous month.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.tallahassee.com/story/news/politics/2023/04/19/in-one-day-three-bills-targeting-transgender-life-pass-florida-house/70130655007/ | title=In one day, three bills targeting transgender Floridians pass House | access-date=May 24, 2023 | archive-date=April 21, 2023 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230421222354/https://www.tallahassee.com/story/news/politics/2023/04/19/in-one-day-three-bills-targeting-transgender-life-pass-florida-house/70130655007/ | url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.losangelesblade.com/2023/05/11/trans-patients-being-dropped-as-florida-law-bans-up-to-80/ |title=Trans patients being dropped as Florida law bans "Up To 80%" |work=Los Angeles Blade |date=May 11, 2023 |access-date=May 24, 2023 |archive-date=May 20, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230520000841/https://www.losangelesblade.com/2023/05/11/trans-patients-being-dropped-as-florida-law-bans-up-to-80/ |url-status=live }}</ref> *[[Missouri]]: In April 2023, the state attorney general issued an emergency order instituting a three-year waiting period of continuous documented dysphoria before qualifying for gender-affirming care, disqualifying people if they have depression, anxiety, or autism, and mandating regular screenings for "social contagion".<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.businessinsider.com/missouri-attorney-general-regulations-gender-affirming-care-transgender-depression-2023-4 | title=Missouri's attorney general opened a new front in the GOP's attacks on transgender people: Banning treatment for any adult with depression | website=[[Business Insider]] | access-date=May 24, 2023 | archive-date=May 14, 2023 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230514114934/https://www.businessinsider.com/missouri-attorney-general-regulations-gender-affirming-care-transgender-depression-2023-4 | url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=https://thehill.com/homenews/state-watch/3949521-missouri-ag-issues-emergency-order-restricting-gender-affirming-health-care/ | title=Missouri AG issues emergency order restricting gender-affirming health care | date=April 13, 2023 | access-date=May 24, 2023 | archive-date=April 21, 2023 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230421200932/https://thehill.com/homenews/state-watch/3949521-missouri-ag-issues-emergency-order-restricting-gender-affirming-health-care/ | url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://ago.mo.gov/docs/default-source/press-releases/2023-04-13---emergency-reg.pdf?sfvrsn=7f78d4fc_2 |title=Archived copy |access-date=May 24, 2023 |archive-date=May 8, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230508231426/https://ago.mo.gov/docs/default-source/press-releases/2023-04-13---emergency-reg.pdf?sfvrsn=7f78d4fc_2 |url-status=live }}</ref> This has been characterized by many as a de facto ban on trans healthcare for adults, since depression and anxiety are common symptoms of gender dysphoria.<ref>{{Cite news |title=Gender-Affirming Care for Adults Is Now Basically Banned in Missouri |work=Vice |url=https://www.vice.com/en/article/bvjzv8/missouri-gender-affirming-care-ban |access-date=May 24, 2023 |archive-date=May 16, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230516064001/https://www.vice.com/en/article/bvjzv8/missouri-gender-affirming-care-ban |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |title=Transgender adults brace for treatment cutoffs in Missouri |work=Seattle Times |url=https://www.seattletimes.com/seattle-news/health/transgender-adults-brace-for-treatment-cutoffs-in-missouri/ |access-date=May 24, 2023 |archive-date=April 29, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230429054250/https://www.seattletimes.com/seattle-news/health/transgender-adults-brace-for-treatment-cutoffs-in-missouri/ |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |title=Missouri AG Directly Cites the New York Times' Anti-Trans Coverage To Justify Horrific New Ban |work=The Mary Sue |url=https://www.themarysue.com/missouri-ag-directly-cites-the-new-york-times-anti-trans-coverage-to-justify-horrific-new-ban/ |access-date=May 24, 2023 |archive-date=May 16, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230516110952/https://www.themarysue.com/missouri-ag-directly-cites-the-new-york-times-anti-trans-coverage-to-justify-horrific-new-ban/ |url-status=live }}</ref> A judge temporarily blocked enforcement of the order and scheduled a hearing for May 11.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Ballentine |first=Summer |date=May 2, 2023 |title=Judge Blocks Missouri Rule That Would Limit Transgender Care |url=https://www.huffpost.com/entry/transgender-health-missouri_n_6450cfaae4b04997b579a580 |access-date=May 2, 2023 |website=HuffPost |language=en |archive-date=May 2, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230502101140/https://www.huffpost.com/entry/transgender-health-missouri_n_6450cfaae4b04997b579a580 |url-status=live }}</ref>
==== Treatment for minors====
Multiple states have banned gender-affirming care for children and adolescents as of 2023.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Mapping Attacks on LGBTQ Rights in U.S. State Legislatures |url=https://www.aclu.org/legislative-attacks-on-lgbtq-rights |access-date=April 7, 2023 |website=American Civil Liberties Union |language=en-US |quote=The ACLU is tracking 452 anti-LGBTQ bills in the U.S. [Page viewed April 7, 2023] |archive-date=April 5, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230405055418/https://www.aclu.org/legislative-attacks-on-lgbtq-rights |url-status=live }}</ref> Some states, like Mississippi and Idaho, have banned all forms of medical transition, while other states, like Arizona and Georgia, have banned only aspects of transition care (such as hormone therapy and [[mastectomy|mastectomies]]). Efforts to prohibit these types of intervention had begun several years earlier, but did not receive much attention from state legislatures until more recently.<ref name="ual2">{{cite web |date=April 6, 2021 |title=Arkansas Lawmakers Override Veto, Enact Transgender Youth Treatment Ban |url=https://www.ualrpublicradio.org/post/arkansas-lawmakers-override-veto-enact-transgender-youth-treatment-ban |website=Associated Press |access-date=May 24, 2023 |archive-date=July 31, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210731220458/https://www.ualrpublicradio.org/post/arkansas-lawmakers-override-veto-enact-transgender-youth-treatment-ban |url-status=live }}</ref> According to ''Newsweek'', in 2023 alone, more than 385 anti-trans bills were submitted in the US, with some legislators advocating for restricting or outright outlawing access to gender-affirming childcare and public facilities.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Khaled |first1=Fatma |title=Thousands of Christians Condemn GOP's 'Fascist' Silencing of Trans Lawmaker |url=https://www.newsweek.com/thousands-christians-condemn-gops-fascist-silencing-trans-lawmaker-1797564 |agency=Newsweek |date=2023 |access-date=May 24, 2023 |archive-date=May 24, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230524121201/https://www.newsweek.com/thousands-christians-condemn-gops-fascist-silencing-trans-lawmaker-1797564 |url-status=live }}</ref>
The conservative organization [[Do No Harm (organization)|Do No Harm]] has been influential in introducing legislation banning gender-affirming care for youth, developing model legislation that has been used starting in 2022 in state legislatures in Arkansas, Florida, Iowa, Mississippi, Montana, New Hampshire, and West Virginia.<ref name=":02">{{Cite web |last1=McMillan |first1=Jeff |last2=Kruesi |first2=Kimberlee |date=2023-05-20 |title=Meet the influential new player on transgender health bills |url=https://apnews.com/article/transgender-bills-lobbying-do-no-harm-94f56059d24608d724eb78fefecf4e09 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230704191142/https://apnews.com/article/transgender-bills-lobbying-do-no-harm-94f56059d24608d724eb78fefecf4e09 |archive-date=2023-07-04 |access-date=2023-09-06 |website=[[AP News]] |language=en}}</ref><ref name=":12">{{Cite web |last=Balevic |first=Katie |title=Do No Harm, a group of 'medical professionals' fighting 'woke healthcare,' is behind many anti-trans laws |url=https://www.businessinsider.com/do-no-harm-behind-anti-trans-laws-fighting-woke-healthcare-2023-5 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230606063139/https://www.businessinsider.com/do-no-harm-behind-anti-trans-laws-fighting-woke-healthcare-2023-5 |archive-date=2023-06-06 |access-date=2023-09-06 |website=[[Business Insider]] |language=en-US}}</ref>
