===Bathroom bills=== {{see also|Bathroom bill}} [[File:Map of current Bathroom Legislation in the United States in regard to Gender and Gender Identity.png|thumb|300px|States and counties in the United States which have enacted legislation on restrooms, locker rooms, and other sex-segregated public accommodations, in regard to their access from those who are transgender, or have gender dysphoria:<br/> ---- {{legend|#9ccb86|State, city, or county mandates single-user unisex restrooms in all public buildings}} {{legend|#009392|State explicitly prohibits discrimination in restrooms on the basis of gender identity}} {{legend|#39b185|State legislation or school guidelines currently '''allow''' students to use restrooms that correspond with gender identity}} ---- {{legend|#e88471|State legislation or school guidelines currently '''prohibit''' students from using restrooms that differ from biological sex}} {{Legend striped|#e88471|white|'''Currently considering''' state legislation or school guidelines that would prohibit students from using restrooms that differ from biological sex}} ---- {{legend|#aa1f4b|State indecent exposure law may be construed to '''criminalize''' trans people from undressing in locker rooms or using restrooms that do not match their biological sex}} {{Legend striped|#aa1f4b|white|'''Currently considering''' bills that may '''criminalize''' trans people from undressing in locker rooms or using restrooms that do not match their biological sex}} ]]
In an early example of an anti-trans bathroom bill, the [[Public Facilities Privacy & Security Act]] in [[North Carolina]], was approved as a law in 2016. The bill, however, sparked widespread condemnation and threats of boycotts, and portions of the measure were repealed in 2017 as part of a compromise between the Democratic governor and Republican-controlled Legislature. Also in 2016, guidance was issued by the U.S. Departments of Justice and Education stating that schools which receive federal money must treat a student's gender identity as their sex (for example, in regard to bathrooms).<ref name="huffingtonpost2">{{cite web |url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/donald-trump-transgender_us_58ac4fe8e4b0a855d1d9d278 |title=Trump Administration Rescinds Protections For Transgender Students &#124; HuffPost |publisher=Huffingtonpost.com |date=February 22, 2017 |access-date=January 18, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180120155803/https://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/donald-trump-transgender_us_58ac4fe8e4b0a855d1d9d278 |archive-date=January 20, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> This policy was revoked in 2017.<ref name="huffingtonpost2" />
In the 2020s, bathroom bills have been proposed and debated in a number of state legislatures. According to the [[American Civil Liberties Union]] there are currently 469 [[anti-LGBTQ]] bills in the US, most targeting transgender people. Current examples include [[Kansas SB 180]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aclu.org/legislative-attacks-on-lgbtq-rights|title=Mapping Attacks on LGBTQ Rights in U.S. State Legislatures|access-date=May 24, 2023|archive-date=April 5, 2023|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230405055418/https://www.aclu.org/legislative-attacks-on-lgbtq-rights|url-status=live}}</ref> Several state bills are based on and closely resemble model legislation provided by the conservative lobbying organization [[Alliance Defending Freedom]] (ADF), which has been classified by the [[Southern Poverty Law Center]] as an anti-LGBT [[hate group]].<ref name="2017.04.08 NBC ADF">{{cite news |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/feature/nbc-out/law-firm-linked-anti-transgender-bathroom-bills-across-country-n741106 |title=This Law Firm Is Linked to Anti-Transgender Bathroom Bills Across the Country |date=April 8, 2017 |first=Mary Emily |last=O'Hara |work=[[NBC News]] |access-date=January 28, 2020 |archive-date=August 5, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170805060139/http://www.nbcnews.com/feature/nbc-out/law-firm-linked-anti-transgender-bathroom-bills-across-country-n741106 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name="WaPo ADF">{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/education/transgender-students-access-to-school-bathrooms-is-new-front-in-war-over-lgbt-rights/2016/02/29/ba66d676-da61-11e5-925f-1d10062cc82d_story.html |url-access=subscription |title=Transgender students' access to bathrooms is at front of LGBT rights battle |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] |date=February 29, 2016 |last1=Brown |first1=Emma |last2=Balingit |first2=Moriah |access-date=January 28, 2020 |archive-date=January 30, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200130025836/https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/education/transgender-students-access-to-school-bathrooms-is-new-front-in-war-over-lgbt-rights/2016/02/29/ba66d676-da61-11e5-925f-1d10062cc82d_story.html |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name="2016.04.25 MJ ADF">{{cite web |url=https://www.motherjones.com/politics/2016/04/alliance-defending-freedom-lobbies-anti-lgbt-bathroom-bills/ |title=We Tracked Down the Lawyers Behind the Recent Wave of Anti-Trans Bathroom Bills |publisher=Mother Jones |last=Michaels |first=Samantha |date=April 25, 2016 |access-date=January 28, 2020 |archive-date=January 30, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200130025837/https://www.motherjones.com/politics/2016/04/alliance-defending-freedom-lobbies-anti-lgbt-bathroom-bills/ |url-status=live }}</ref> The ADF's model legislation proposes giving any public school or university student the right to sue for $2,500 for each time they encountered a transgender classmate in a locker room or bathroom.<ref name="2017.04.08 NBC ADF"/><ref name="ADF Model Bathroom Bill">{{cite web |url=https://www.facingsouth.org/sites/default/files/ADF-model-legislation.pdf |title=Testimony of Michael J. Norton, Senior Counsel, Alliance Defending Freedom |publisher=Alliance Defending Freedom |date=February 4, 2015 |access-date=January 28, 2020 |archive-date=January 19, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210119203723/https://www.facingsouth.org/sites/default/files/ADF-model-legislation.pdf |url-status=live }}</ref>
A number of the bills put forth and passed made it some form of criminal offense, often a [[Sex offender registries in the United States|sex offense]], for a transgender person to use a bathroom, locker room, changing room, or other similar facility not corresponding with their assigned sex. The most severe of these was that of Arkansas, which made it an offense of "sexual indecency with a child" for a trans person to use any such facility if said facility contained anyone under 18 at the time of use.<ref>{{Cite act|type=Senate Bill|index=270|date=2023|legislature=Arkansas State Legislature|url=https://www.arkleg.state.ar.us/Bills/FTPDocument?path=%2FBills%2F2023R%2FPublic%2FSB270.pdf}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Shapero |first=Julia |date=2023-05-04 |title=Florida passes transgender bathroom bill |url=https://thehill.com/homenews/state-watch/3987176-florida-passes-transgender-bathroom-bill/ |access-date=2023-05-04 |website=The Hill |language=en-US |archive-date=May 16, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230516150350/https://thehill.com/homenews/state-watch/3987176-florida-passes-transgender-bathroom-bill/ |url-status=live }}</ref>
Since 2021, Alabama, Arkansas, Oklahoma, Tennessee, and Idaho have enacted bathroom bills.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Migdon |first=Brooke |date=March 24, 2023 |title=Idaho governor signs transgender bathroom bill |url=https://thehill.com/homenews/state-watch/3916944-idaho-governor-signs-transgender-bathroom-bill/ |access-date=April 22, 2023 |website=The Hill |language=en-US |quote=At least three other states — Alabama, Oklahoma and Tennessee — have enacted so-called bathroom bills since 2021. |archive-date=April 22, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230422184233/https://thehill.com/homenews/state-watch/3916944-idaho-governor-signs-transgender-bathroom-bill/ |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |date=April 11, 2023 |title=Act 619 |url=https://www.arkleg.state.ar.us/Acts/FTPDocument?path=%2FACTS%2F2023R%2FPublic%2F&file=619.pdf&ddBienniumSession=2023%2F2023R |access-date=April 22, 2023 |website=www.arkleg.state.ar.us |archive-date=April 22, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230422184235/https://www.arkleg.state.ar.us/Acts/FTPDocument?path=/ACTS/2023R/Public/&file=619.pdf&ddBienniumSession=2023/2023R |url-status=live }}</ref> State legislatures in Arizona, Illinois, Kansas, Kentucky, Massachusetts, Minnesota, Mississippi, Missouri, South Carolina, Tennessee, and Texas have proposed bathroom bills. The [[National Center for Transgender Equality]], an LGBTQ advocacy group, calls these bills discriminatory.<ref>National Center for Transgender Equality. "Take Action Against Anti-Trans Legislation Now!" Retrieved from {{cite web |date=January 23, 2016 |title=Take Action Against Anti-Trans Legislation Now! |url=http://www.transequality.org/action-center#Hawaii |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161121204915/http://www.transequality.org/action-center |archive-date=November 21, 2016 |access-date=March 22, 2016}}</ref>
In December 2022, sitting ''en banc'', the [[United States Court of Appeals for the Eleventh Circuit]] ruled in ''[[Adams ex rel. Kasper v. School Board of St. Johns County, Florida]]'' that separating the use of male and female bathrooms in public schools based on a student's biological sex doesn't violate the Equal Protection Clause of the Fourteenth Amendment or Title IX of the Education Amendments Act of 1972.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Appeals court rules against transgender man in bathroom case |url=https://abcnews.go.com/US/wireStory/appeals-court-rules-transgender-man-bathroom-case-96020070 |date=December 31, 2022 |website=ABC News |language=en |access-date=June 21, 2023 |archive-date=May 23, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230523045147/https://abcnews.go.com/US/wireStory/appeals-court-rules-transgender-man-bathroom-case-96020070 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>[[Adams ex rel. Kasper v. School Board of St. Johns County, Florida (2022)|Adams ex rel. Kasper v. School Board of St. Johns County, Florida, No. 18-13592 (11th Cir. December 30, 2022).]] {{full citation|date=September 2023}}</ref> Previously, in August 2020, a three judge panel of the [[United States Court of Appeals for the Eleventh Circuit]] affirmed a 2018 lower court ruling in ''Adams v. The School Board of St. Johns County'' that discrimination on the basis of gender identity is discrimination "on the basis of sex" and is prohibited under Title IX (federal civil rights law) and the [[Equal Protection Clause]] of the [[14th Amendment to the US Constitution]].<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.lambdalegal.org/in-court/cases/fl_adams-v-school-board-st-johns-county | title = Adams v. The School Board of St. Johns County, Florida | access-date = August 23, 2020 | work = [[Lambda Legal]] | archive-date = September 16, 2020 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20200916070947/https://www.lambdalegal.org/in-court/cases/fl_adams-v-school-board-st-johns-county | url-status = live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = http://media.ca11.uscourts.gov/opinions/pub/files/201813592.pdf | title = Adams v. The School Board of St. Johns County, Florida | date = August 7, 2020 | access-date = August 23, 2020 | work = [[United States Court of Appeals for the Eleventh Circuit]] | archive-date = August 14, 2020 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20200814114929/http://media.ca11.uscourts.gov/opinions/pub/files/201813592.pdf | url-status = live }}</ref>
{{clear}}
==Anti-drag behavior== {{main article|Drag panic}} [[File:Drag Queen Story Hour Protest - 52452239331.png|thumb|People protesting against [[Drag Queen Story Hour]] in 2022.]]
=== Protests === Protests against drag performances, especially [[Drag Queen Story Hour]], increased after the [[January 6 United States Capitol attack|2021 attack at the United States Capitol]].<ref name="Brend-2022">{{Cite news |last=Brend |first=Yvette |date=December 15, 2022 |title=Drag storytimes have become a target of hate. Why some families love them anyway |work=CBC |url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/drag-queen-storytime-attacks-usa-canada-diversity-inclusion-hate-groups-gender-1.6685395 |access-date=March 24, 2023 |archive-date=March 17, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230317192717/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/drag-queen-storytime-attacks-usa-canada-diversity-inclusion-hate-groups-gender-1.6685395 |url-status=live }}</ref> The most vocal opponents are mostly affiliated with [[alt-right]] groups.<ref name="Brend-2022" /> Former ''[[Fox News]]'' host, Tucker Carlson, suggested that drag events could "indoctrinate or sexualize" children.<ref name="Brend-2022" /> Protestors also have expressed concern about homophobic conspiracy theories that performers are grooming children.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Ottenhof |first=Luke |date=November 29, 2022 |title='I don't feel safe': Ontario drag performers reckon with heightened risk |url=https://www.tvo.org/article/i-dont-feel-safe-ontario-drag-performers-reckon-with-heightened-risk |access-date=December 31, 2022 |website=www.tvo.org |archive-date=December 21, 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221221013147/https://www.tvo.org/article/i-dont-feel-safe-ontario-drag-performers-reckon-with-heightened-risk |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=What is "Grooming?" The Truth Behind the Dangerous, Bigoted Lie Targeting the LGBTQ+ Community {{!}} ADL |url=https://www.adl.org/resources/blog/what-grooming-truth-behind-dangerous-bigoted-lie-targeting-lgbtq-community |access-date=December 31, 2022 |website=www.adl.org |language=en |archive-date=February 13, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230213082215/https://www.adl.org/resources/blog/what-grooming-truth-behind-dangerous-bigoted-lie-targeting-lgbtq-community |url-status=live }}</ref> The [[Anti-Defamation League]] reported that child abuse conspiracy theory has been fueled by the [[Libs of TikTok]], a far-right Twitter account.<ref name="GLAAD-2022" /> The [[GLAAD|Gay & Lesbian Alliance Against Defamation]] reported over 120 threats against drag shows in the US, throughout 2022.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Simpson |first=Katie |date=December 8, 2022 |title=As drag shows in the U.S. are increasingly targeted, the community fears violence |work=CBC |url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/world/drag-shows-targeted-us-1.6677999 |access-date=March 24, 2023 |archive-date=March 18, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230318173233/https://www.cbc.ca/news/world/drag-shows-targeted-us-1.6677999 |url-status=live }}</ref>
In mid-June 2022, the Twitter account, Libs of TikTok, condemned the upcoming [[Coeur d'Alene, Idaho]]'s "Pride in the Park" festival due to a "family-friendly drag performance."<ref name="GLAAD-2022">{{Cite web |title=UPDATED GLAAD Report: Drag events faced at least 141 protests and significant threats in 2022 |url=https://www.glaad.org/blog/glaad-report-drag-events-faced-least-124-protests-and-significant-threats-2022 |access-date=March 3, 2023 |website=GLAAD |date=November 21, 2022 |language=en |archive-date=March 3, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230303045901/https://www.glaad.org/blog/glaad-report-drag-events-faced-least-124-protests-and-significant-threats-2022 |url-status=live }}</ref> On June 11, 2022, during the pride event, law enforcement arrested 31 members of the white nationalist and hate group [[Patriot Front]], later charging them with conspiracy to riot.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Hayden |first=Michael Edison |date=June 14, 2022 |title=FAR-RIGHT INFLUENCERS HYPED COEUR D'ALENE PRIDE BEFORE PATRIOT FRONT SHOWED UP |work=[[Southern Poverty Law Center]] |url=https://www.splcenter.org/hatewatch/2022/06/14/far-right-influencers-hyped-coeur-dalene-pride-patriot-front-showed |access-date=March 22, 2023 |archive-date=March 24, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230324164452/https://www.splcenter.org/hatewatch/2022/06/14/far-right-influencers-hyped-coeur-dalene-pride-patriot-front-showed |url-status=live }}</ref> In May 2023, masked [[neo-Nazism|neo-Nazi]] groups in [[Ohio]] protested drag events in [[Wadsworth, Ohio|Wadsworth]] and [[Columbus, Ohio|Columbus]], carrying anti-drag and [[Transphobia|anti-trans]] banners, such as one that read, "There Will Be Blood."<ref>{{cite web |last1=McNeill |first1=Zane |title=Nazis Carrying Banner That Says, "There Will Be Blood" Protest Ohio Drag Brunch |url=https://truthout.org/articles/nazis-carrying-banner-that-says-there-will-be-blood-protest-ohio-drag-brunch/ |website=Truthout |date=May 2, 2023 |access-date=May 15, 2023 |archive-date=May 15, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230515183405/https://truthout.org/articles/nazis-carrying-banner-that-says-there-will-be-blood-protest-ohio-drag-brunch/ |url-status=live }}</ref> A report from [[GLAAD]] noted there 138 documented incidents of anti-LGBTQ harassment, vandalism or assault at drag shows in the United States from June 2022 through April 2023.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Astor |first1=Maggie |title=Report Cites More Than 350 Anti-L.G.B.T.Q. Incidents Over 11 Months |work=The New York Times |date=June 22, 2023 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2023/06/22/us/politics/anti-lgbtq-report-adl-glaad.html |access-date=June 26, 2023 |archive-date=June 26, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230626092749/https://www.nytimes.com/2023/06/22/us/politics/anti-lgbtq-report-adl-glaad.html |url-status=live }}</ref> An Institute for Strategic Dialogue report indicated that the [[Proud Boys]] were the leading group spreading anti-LGBT sentiment.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Alfonseca |first=Kiara |title=Rise in anti-LGBTQ hate and extremism captured in new reports |url=https://abcnews.go.com/US/rise-anti-lgbtq-hate-extremism-captured-new-reports/story?id=100304706 |date=June 22, 2023 |access-date=2023-08-10 |website=ABC News |language=en |archive-date=August 9, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230809172254/https://abcnews.go.com/US/rise-anti-lgbtq-hate-extremism-captured-new-reports/story?id=100304706 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |date=2023-06-22 |title=US leads global threat to drag events: 'Backsliding toward hate and violence' |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/americas/drag-queen-story-protests-proud-boys-b2361981.html |access-date=2023-08-10 |website=The Independent |language=en |archive-date=August 11, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230811022346/https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/americas/drag-queen-story-protests-proud-boys-b2361981.html |url-status=live }}</ref>
=== Laws and restrictions === On March 2, 2023, [[Tennessee]] governor [[Bill Lee (Tennessee politician)|Bill Lee]] signed the [[Tennessee Adult Entertainment Act|Adult Entertainment Act]], which prohibits drag performances for children.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Tennessee governor signs first-of-its-kind bill restricting drag shows |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/feature/nbc-out/tennessee-governor-signs-first-its-kind-bill-restricting-drag-shows-n1303262 |access-date=March 3, 2023 |website=NBC News |date=March 3, 2023 |language=en |archive-date=March 3, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230303042552/https://www.nbcnews.com/feature/nbc-out/tennessee-governor-signs-first-its-kind-bill-restricting-drag-shows-n1303262 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Fiscus |first1=Kirsten |title=Tennessee drag show bill: Will drag performances be banned? What we know. |url=https://www.tennessean.com/story/news/politics/2023/03/01/tennessee-drag-bill-will-drag-shows-and-performances-be-banned/69949236007/ |access-date=July 22, 2023 |work=[[The Tennessean]] |publisher=[[Gannett]] |date=March 1, 2023 |archive-date=August 21, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230821070628/https://www.tennessean.com/story/news/politics/2023/03/01/tennessee-drag-bill-will-drag-shows-and-performances-be-banned/69949236007/ |url-status=live }}</ref> This bill sparked outrage from the LGBT community.<ref>{{cite web |last=Baker-Jordan |first=Skylar |date=March 2, 2023 |title=Why the Tennessee ban on drag shows should terrify us all |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/voices/tennessee-drag-show-ban-queens-b2289083.html |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230308023652/http://www.independent.co.uk/voices/tennessee-drag-show-ban-queens-b2289083.html |archive-date=March 8, 2023 |access-date=March 8, 2023 |website=[[The Independent]]}}</ref> The states of [[Florida]], [[Montana]], and [[Texas]] also banned public drag performances in 2023.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Riley |first1=John |title=Texas Governor Signs Law Banning Drag Performances in Public Businesses |url=https://www.metroweekly.com/2023/06/texas-governor-signs-law-banning-drag-performances-in-public/ |website=Metro Weekly |date=June 23, 2023 |access-date=June 26, 2023 |archive-date=June 26, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230626003837/https://www.metroweekly.com/2023/06/texas-governor-signs-law-banning-drag-performances-in-public/ |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Mizelle |first1=Shawna |title=Montana governor signs bill banning drag performers from reading to children in public schools, libraries |url=https://www.cnn.com/2023/05/24/politics/montana-drag-story-hour-ban/index.html |website=CNN |date=May 24, 2023 |access-date=June 26, 2023 |archive-date=June 26, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230626154342/https://www.cnn.com/2023/05/24/politics/montana-drag-story-hour-ban/index.html |url-status=live }}</ref> Both the Florida and Tennessee drag bans were halted in court.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Kashiwagi |first1=Sydney |title=Trump-appointed federal judge rules Tennessee's anti-drag show law is 'unconstitutional' |url=https://www.cnn.com/2023/06/03/politics/tennessee-drag-ban-law-unconstitutional/index.html |website=CNN |date=June 3, 2023 |access-date=June 26, 2023 |archive-date=June 26, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230626154342/https://www.cnn.com/2023/06/03/politics/tennessee-drag-ban-law-unconstitutional/index.html |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Trotta |first1=Daniel |title=U.S. court blocks Florida law restricting drag performances |url=https://www.reuters.com/legal/us-court-blocks-florida-law-restricting-drag-performances-2023-06-23/ |website=Reuters |date=June 23, 2023 |access-date=June 26, 2023 |archive-date=June 26, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230626154342/https://www.reuters.com/legal/us-court-blocks-florida-law-restricting-drag-performances-2023-06-23/ |url-status=live }}</ref>
== Marriage == [[File:Respect for Marriage Act Senate Map.png|thumb|Map image of senatorial votes for the Respect for Marriage Act (2022).]] In response to a concurring opinion by Justice [[Clarence Thomas]] in ''[[Dobbs v. Jackson Women's Health Organization]]'' arguing the Court should reconsider ''[[Obergefell v. Hodges]]'', Congress passed the [[Respect for Marriage Act]] in 2022.<ref>{{cite web |last=Sneed |first=Tierney |title=Supreme Court's decision on abortion could open the door to overturn same-sex marriage, contraception and other major rulings |url=https://www.cnn.com/2022/06/24/politics/abortion-ruling-gay-rights-contraceptives/index.html |website=CNN |date=June 24, 2022 |access-date=July 18, 2022 |archive-date=June 24, 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220624174858/https://www.cnn.com/2022/06/24/politics/abortion-ruling-gay-rights-contraceptives/index.html |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Gerstein |first1=Josh |title=Justice Thomas: SCOTUS "should reconsider" contraception, same-sex marriage rulings |url=https://www.politico.com/news/2022/06/24/thomas-constitutional-rights-00042256 |website=Politico |date=June 24, 2022 |access-date=July 18, 2022 |archive-date=July 18, 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220718031321/https://www.politico.com/news/2022/06/24/thomas-constitutional-rights-00042256 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine |last1=Carlisle |first1=Madeline |title=Clarence Thomas Signals Same-Sex Marriage and Contraception Rights at Risk After Overturning Roe v. Wade |url=https://time.com/6191044/clarence-thomas-same-sex-marriage-contraception-abortion/ |magazine=Time |access-date=July 18, 2022 |archive-date=July 17, 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220717190345/https://time.com/6191044/clarence-thomas-same-sex-marriage-contraception-abortion/ |url-status=live }}</ref> RFMA officially repealed the [[Defense of Marriage Act]] and required the federal government to recognize same-sex and interracial marriages, thus codifying parts of ''Obergefell,'' the 2013 ruling in ''[[United States v. Windsor]]'', and the 1967 ruling in ''[[Loving v. Virginia]]''.<ref name="Somin">{{cite web |last1=Somin |first1=Ilya |title=Federalism and the Respect for Marriage Act |url=https://reason.com/volokh/2022/07/20/federalism-and-the-respect-for-marriage-act/ |website=[[Reason (magazine)|Reason]] |date=July 20, 2022|access-date=July 20, 2022 |archive-date=July 23, 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220723181719/https://reason.com/volokh/2022/07/20/federalism-and-the-respect-for-marriage-act/ |url-status=live }}</ref> In addition, it compelled all U.S. states and territories to recognize the validity of same-sex and interracial marriages if performed in a jurisdiction where such marriages are legally performed; however, it does not legally compel states to perform same-sex marriages if ''Obergefell'' is overturned.
The following year, the [[Tennessee House of Representatives]] passed [[Tennessee House Bill 878|House Bill 878]], which would grant an individual the right to refuse to [[wikt:solemnization|solemnize]] a marriage if the individual has a religious or conscience-based objection to that partnership.<ref name="Tennessee May Allow Clerks">{{cite web |last1=Ring |first1=Trudy |title=Tennessee May Allow Clerks to Refuse Marriage Licenses to Same-Sex Couples |url=https://news.yahoo.com/tennessee-may-allow-clerks-refuse-194530269.html |website=yahoo! news |date=March 9, 2023 |access-date=15 March 2023 |archive-date=March 26, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230326054845/https://news.yahoo.com/tennessee-may-allow-clerks-refuse-194530269.html |url-status=live }}</ref> In Texas, [[McLennan County, Texas|McLennan County]] [[Justice of the peace|Justice of the Peace]] Dianne Hensley filed a lawsuit to allow her to refuse to marry gay couples, citing the 2023 U.S. Supreme Court case ''[[303 Creative LLC v. Elenis]]''.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Schneid |first1=Rebecca |title=Texas judge who doesn't want to perform gay marriage ceremonies hopes web designer's Supreme Court case helps her fight |url=https://www.texastribune.org/2023/07/12/texas-judge-gay-weddings-supreme-court/ |website=Texas Tribune |date=July 12, 2023 |access-date=14 July 2023 |archive-date=July 14, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230714150205/https://www.texastribune.org/2023/07/12/texas-judge-gay-weddings-supreme-court/ |url-status=live }}</ref>
== Book bans == {{main article|2021–2023 book banning in the United States}}
Legislation was introduced or passed in at least 29 states taking aim at lessons that teach children about race and LGBT people, with most of the laws framed around putting a stop to critical race theory and gender ideology.<ref>{{cite magazine |last1=Bond-Theriault |first1=Candace |title=The Right Targets Queer Theory |url=https://www.thenation.com/article/society/christopher-rufo-queer-theory/ |website=The Nation |date=April 19, 2022 |access-date=May 24, 2023 |archive-date=May 24, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230524144723/https://www.thenation.com/article/society/christopher-rufo-queer-theory/ |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name="Alfonseca-2021">{{Cite web|last=Alfonseca|first=Kiara|date=December 3, 2021|title=Authors of color speak out against efforts to ban books on race|url=https://abcnews.go.com/US/authors-color-speak-efforts-ban-books-race/story?id=81491208|access-date=February 13, 2022|website=ABC News|language=en|archive-date=February 14, 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220214004449/https://abcnews.go.com/US/authors-color-speak-efforts-ban-books-race/story?id=81491208|url-status=live}}</ref> These laws, which use broad language prohibiting teaching about privilege related to race or sex, or systemic bias in the United States, have led to many book removals.<ref name="Alfonseca-2021"/><ref name="Will-2021">{{Cite news|last=Will|first=Madeline|date=September 30, 2021|title=Calls to Ban Books by Black Authors Are Increasing Amid Critical Race Theory Debates|language=en|work=Education Week|url=https://www.edweek.org/teaching-learning/calls-to-ban-books-by-black-authors-are-increasing-amid-critical-race-theory-debates/2021/09|access-date=February 13, 2022|issn=0277-4232|archive-date=February 13, 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220213181741/https://www.edweek.org/teaching-learning/calls-to-ban-books-by-black-authors-are-increasing-amid-critical-race-theory-debates/2021/09|url-status=live}}</ref> NBC News described the use of the term "critical race theory" in this context as "a catch-all term to refer to what schools often call equity programs, teaching about racism or LGBTQ-inclusive policies".<ref name="Kingkade-2021">{{Cite web|last1=Kingkade|first1=Tyler|last2=Zadrozny|first2=Brandy|author-link2=Brandy Zadrozny|last3=Collins|first3=Ben|date=June 15, 2021|title=Critical race theory battle invades school boards — with help from conservative groups|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/us-news/critical-race-theory-invades-school-boards-help-conservative-groups-n1270794|access-date=February 13, 2022|website=NBC News|language=en|archive-date=June 16, 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210616033841/https://www.nbcnews.com/news/us-news/critical-race-theory-invades-school-boards-help-conservative-groups-n1270794|url-status=live}}</ref> ''[[The Takeaway]]''<nowiki/>'s [[Melissa Harris-Perry]] cited discomfort with issues like [[gender identity]] as one of the common reasons for challenges, but that "this discomfort is likely imposed by adults onto young learners" who are otherwise more accepting and more likely to think outside traditional [[gender role]]s.<ref name="The Takeaway-2022">{{Cite web|date=February 8, 2022|title=Division over Critical Race Theory's Meaning Has Spurred A Rise in Book Bans|url=https://www.wnycstudios.org/podcasts/takeaway/segments/division-critical-race-theory-spurred-rise-book-ban|access-date=February 13, 2022|website=The Takeaway|language=en|archive-date=February 13, 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220213043649/https://www.wnycstudios.org/podcasts/takeaway/segments/division-critical-race-theory-spurred-rise-book-ban|url-status=live}}</ref>
An example of such bans is that passed by Florida in March 2022, which created a list of sanctioned reading material for students in educational settings, and punished any teacher or school librarian whose classrooms or libraries contained unsanctioned books with felony charges. Sanctioned books must be reviewed by the state to be free of "prohibited material harmful to minors", which critics have said that under Florida state law includes content regarding the LGBT community and black history.<ref>{{Cite news|date=January 27, 2023|last1=Hall|first1=Richard|work=The Independent|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/americas/us-politics/ron-desantis-book-bans-florida-b2270116.html|title='I've never seen anything like it': Florida teachers strip classroom shelves of books in response to DeSantis ban|access-date=July 14, 2023|archive-date=June 1, 2023|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230601083444/https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/americas/us-politics/ron-desantis-book-bans-florida-b2270116.html|url-status=live}}</ref>
== Boycotts == {{Tweet | name = Matt Walsh | username = MattWalshBlog | text = The goal is to make "pride" toxic for brands. If they decide to shove this garbage in our face, they should know that they'll pay a price. It won't be worth whatever they think they'll gain. First Bud Light and now Target. Our campaign is making progress. Let's keep it going. | date = May 24, 2023 | reference = <ref>{{cite web |last1=Walsh |first1=Matt |title=Tweet |url=https://twitter.com/MattWalshBlog/status/1661333191951613952 |website=Twitter |access-date=May 24, 2023 |archive-date=May 24, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230524194617/https://twitter.com/MattWalshBlog/status/1661333191951613952 |url-status=live }}</ref> | ID = 1500129642 | image = Matt Walsh (cropped).jpg | width = 300px }} Conservative activists urged for [[boycotting]] any company which publicly supported, or collaborated with members of, the LGBT community.<ref name="LGBTQ Culture Wars">{{cite web |last1=Murray |first1=Conor |title=LGBTQ Culture Wars Increasingly Target Companies—And Nike, Adidas And Ford Are Only The Latest |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/conormurray/2023/05/20/far-right-pundits-are-slamming-companies-including-nike-adidas-and-ford-for-lgbtq-outreach-as-pride-month-nears/?sh=3ee346c776d0 |website=Forbes |access-date=May 24, 2023 |archive-date=May 24, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230524150702/https://www.forbes.com/sites/conormurray/2023/05/20/far-right-pundits-are-slamming-companies-including-nike-adidas-and-ford-for-lgbtq-outreach-as-pride-month-nears/?sh=3ee346c776d0 |url-status=live }}</ref> Some of the most well-known examples included the [[2023 Anheuser-Busch boycott]] against [[Bud Light]] for a sponsorship with actress and TikToker [[Dylan Mulvaney]],<ref>{{cite web |date=April 25, 2023 |title=Anti-trans backlash against Bud Light has executives on the hot seat. What's going on? |url=https://www.latimes.com/business/story/2023-04-25/anti-transgender-backlash-against-bud-light-explained |access-date=April 27, 2023 |website=Los Angeles Times |archive-date=April 27, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230427015158/https://www.latimes.com/business/story/2023-04-25/anti-transgender-backlash-against-bud-light-explained |url-status=live }}</ref> and the campaign against [[Disney]] by Florida governor [[Ron DeSantis]] for publicly opposing the state's Anti-LGBT curriculum law.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Sampson |first1=Hannah |title=Conservatives want to cancel Disney. It's not the first time. |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/travel/2022/04/18/disney-boycott-theme-parks-lgbtq/ |newspaper=Washington Post |access-date=May 24, 2023 |archive-date=April 2, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230402083206/https://www.washingtonpost.com/travel/2022/04/18/disney-boycott-theme-parks-lgbtq/ |url-status=live }}</ref> Other targeted companies include [[Nike, Inc.|Nike]], [[Adidas]] and [[Ford Motor Company|Ford]].<ref name="LGBTQ Culture Wars"/> In May 2023, [[Target Corporation|Target]] removed several Pride Month items from stores in the Southern United States after anti-LGBTQ hate groups [[2023 Target Pride Month merchandise backlash|threatened]] violence against its employees.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Guynn |first1=Jessica |title=Target removes LGBTQ Pride month merchandise after threats |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/money/2023/05/23/bud-light-moment-as-target-removes-pride-lgbtq-merchandise/70250377007/ |website=USA Today |access-date=May 24, 2023 |archive-date=May 24, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230524012334/https://www.usatoday.com/story/money/2023/05/23/bud-light-moment-as-target-removes-pride-lgbtq-merchandise/70250377007/ |url-status=live }}</ref>
== Violence == {{further|History of violence against LGBT people in the United States}} According to a 2023 report by the [[Department of Homeland Security]], threats of violence against the LGBT community rose in the early-2020s.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Margolin |first1=Josh |title=Threats against the LGBTQIA+ community intensifying: Department of Homeland Security |url=https://abcnews.go.com/US/threats-lgbtqia-community-intensifying-department-homeland-security/story?id=99338137 |website=ABC News |access-date=21 August 2023 |archive-date=August 20, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230820002223/https://abcnews.go.com/US/threats-lgbtqia-community-intensifying-department-homeland-security/story?id=99338137 |url-status=live }}</ref> The [[FBI]] also noted a sharp uptick in the number of [[hate crimes]] committed against LGBT people, with the 54 percent increase representing the fastest rise in hate crimes of all groups in the country.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Bernal |first1=Rafael |title=Hate crimes up by double digits last year: FBI |url=https://thehill.com/blogs/blog-briefing-room/news/3898187-hate-crimes-up-by-double-digits-last-year-fbi/ |website=The Hill |date=March 13, 2023 |access-date=21 August 2023 |archive-date=August 7, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230807111605/https://thehill.com/blogs/blog-briefing-room/news/3898187-hate-crimes-up-by-double-digits-last-year-fbi/ |url-status=live }}</ref> In [[New York City]], hate crimes against LGBT people doubled from 2021 to 2022, and they grew by 29% in California during the same period.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Krauth |first1=Dan |title=Hate crimes up by nearly 50% in LGBTQ+ community across New York City |url=https://abc7ny.com/hate-crime-lgbtq-new-york-city-pride-month/11958809/ |website=ABC 7 NY |date=June 14, 2022 |access-date=21 August 2023 |archive-date=March 28, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230328170745/https://abc7ny.com/hate-crime-lgbtq-new-york-city-pride-month/11958809/ |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Sternfield |first1=Marc |title=Hate crimes targeting California's gay community rose by 29% in 2022, report says |url=https://ktla.com/news/california/hate-crimes-targeting-californias-gay-community-rose-by-29-in-2022-report-says/ |website=KTLA |date=June 20, 2023 |access-date=21 August 2023 |archive-date=July 4, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230704204720/https://ktla.com/news/california/hate-crimes-targeting-californias-gay-community-rose-by-29-in-2022-report-says/ |url-status=live }}</ref> In August 2023, [[Killing of Laura Ann Carleton|Lauri Carleton]], a business owner in [[Southern California]], was shot and killed for keeping a [[pride flag]] outside her store.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Franklin |first1=Jonathan |title=A California store owner was shot and killed over a Pride flag displayed at her shop |url=https://www.npr.org/2023/08/20/1194932544/lauri-carleton-california-store-owner-killed-pride-flag-lgbtq |website=NPR |access-date=21 August 2023 |archive-date=August 21, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230821070717/https://www.npr.org/2023/08/20/1194932544/lauri-carleton-california-store-owner-killed-pride-flag-lgbtq |url-status=live }}</ref>
== Public opinion ==
According to the [[Public Religion Research Institute]], support for mandating that trans people use the bathroom corresponding to their gender assigned at birth rose among all religious groups, with white evangelical Protestants seeing the largest change, going from 41% in support to 72% in support between 2017 and 2021. 41% of total Americans held this stance, with 31% disagreeing, and 28% not taking either position.<ref name="auto">{{Cite news |url= https://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/2023/02/21/trump-gender-lgbtq-identity/ |title= Trump is exploiting an anti-trans turn in public opinion |work= WaPo |date= Feb 21, 2023 |access-date= July 13, 2023 |archive-date= February 23, 2023 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20230223144538/https://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/2023/02/21/trump-gender-lgbtq-identity/ |url-status= live }}</ref>
60% of American adults reported in the summer of 2022 that they opposed allowing nonbinary marker options on government documents, while 58% reported supporting mandating that trans athletes compete on teams matching their gender assigned at birth.<ref name="auto"/>
== Media involvement == {{See also|The New York Times#Transgender rights and healthcare}}
Supporters of LGBT rights argue that major US media outlets have taken part in furthering the backlash by publishing and promoting stories criticized by many experts and advocates as misinformation, fringe theories, fearmongering, and pseudoscience about LGBT people, and in particular trans people.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://sciencebasedmedicine.org/what-the-new-york-times-gets-wrong-about-puberty-blockers-for-transgender-youth/ |work=Science Based Medicine |title=What the New York Times gets wrong about puberty blockers for transgender youth |access-date=July 13, 2023 |archive-date=December 5, 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221205135645/https://sciencebasedmedicine.org/what-the-new-york-times-gets-wrong-about-puberty-blockers-for-transgender-youth/ |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://slate.com/technology/2022/11/puberty-blockers-side-effects-controversy.html |work=Slate |title=The NYT's Big Piece on Puberty Blockers Mucked Up the Most Important Point About Them |access-date=July 13, 2023 |archive-date=November 18, 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221118235100/https://slate.com/technology/2022/11/puberty-blockers-side-effects-controversy.html |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite magazine |magazine=Vanity Fair |url=https://www.vanityfair.com/news/2023/02/new-york-times-trans-coverage |title=Nearly 200 New York Times Contributors Are Denouncing the Paper's Anti-Trans Coverage}}</ref> Among these outlets were [[Reuters]], [[Fox News]], ''[[The Washington Post]]'', ''[[The Atlantic]]'', and most prolifically, ''[[The New York Times]]''.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://theintercept.com/2022/12/31/trans-rights-abortion-liberals/ |work=The Intercept |date=December 31, 2022 |title=Liberals Rose to Fight the Assault on Abortion — but Not Trans Rights |access-date=July 13, 2023 |archive-date=August 8, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230808122507/https://theintercept.com/2022/12/31/trans-rights-abortion-liberals/ |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.mediamatters.org/fox-news/doom-groom-fox-news-has-aired-170-segments-discussing-trans-people-past-three-weeks |title="Doom & Groom": Fox News has aired 170 segments discussing trans people in the past three weeks |last1=Paterson |first1=Alex |website=[[Media Matters for America]] |date=April 8, 2022 |access-date=May 24, 2023 |archive-date=June 1, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230601182823/https://www.mediamatters.org/fox-news/doom-groom-fox-news-has-aired-170-segments-discussing-trans-people-past-three-weeks |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2023/feb/17/new-york-times-contributors-open-letter-protest-anti-trans-coverage |work=The Guardian |title=Nearly 1,000 contributors protest New York Times' coverage of trans people |access-date=July 13, 2023 |archive-date=June 17, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230617004638/https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2023/feb/17/new-york-times-contributors-open-letter-protest-anti-trans-coverage |url-status=live }}</ref> These pieces have often been cited in legislation and court cases to restrict LGBT rights.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.vox.com/culture/23652475/trans-issues-in-the-media-healthcare-disinformation |work=Vox |title=Trans people deserve better journalism |access-date=July 13, 2023 |archive-date=July 5, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230705021303/https://www.vox.com/culture/23652475/trans-issues-in-the-media-healthcare-disinformation |url-status=live }}</ref>
== Responses == === Domestic === ====Refugees==== Some trans people and their families have fled<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/nbc-out/out-politics-and-policy/texas-families-trans-kids-plan-flee-state-rcna23633 |title=More Texas families with trans kids plan to flee the state |last1=Yurcaba |first1=Jo |website=[[NBC News]] |date=April 11, 2022 |access-date=July 16, 2023 |archive-date=July 27, 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220727001452/https://www.nbcnews.com/nbc-out/out-politics-and-policy/texas-families-trans-kids-plan-flee-state-rcna23633 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.motherjones.com/politics/2022/03/trans-teens-texas-medical-care-abbott-paxton-bigotry/ |last1=Michaels |first1=Samantha |title=Transgender Teens and Their Families Prepare to Flee Texas |access-date=July 16, 2023 |archive-date=August 11, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230811082126/https://www.motherjones.com/politics/2022/03/trans-teens-texas-medical-care-abbott-paxton-bigotry/ |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/nbc-out/out-community-voices/texas-trans-activist-kai-shappley-flees-state-years-advocacy-rcna37000 |title=Texas trans activist, 11, flees the state after years of advocacy |last1=Yurcaba |first1=Jo |website=[[NBC News]] |date=July 7, 2022 |access-date=July 16, 2023 |archive-date=June 30, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230630105724/https://www.nbcnews.com/nbc-out/out-community-voices/texas-trans-activist-kai-shappley-flees-state-years-advocacy-rcna37000 |url-status=live }}</ref> to other states or countries, including the families of those who actively advocated against anti-trans laws in their states.<ref>{{cite magazine |last1=Carlisle |first1=Madeleine |title=As Texas Targets Trans Youth, a Family Leaves in Search of a Better Future |url=https://time.com/6196617/trans-kids-texas-leave/ |magazine=[[Time (magazine)|Time]] |date=July 14, 2022}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Ernst |first1=Sara |title=Texas families with trans kids are leaving the state |url=https://www.npr.org/2022/04/27/1095099695/texas-families-with-trans-kids-are-leaving-the-state |work=[[NPR]] |date=April 27, 2022 |access-date=July 22, 2023 |archive-date=July 22, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230722060859/https://www.npr.org/2022/04/27/1095099695/texas-families-with-trans-kids-are-leaving-the-state |url-status=live }}</ref> Many families cite increasing social pressure and restrictions on gender-affirming care as reasons for moving.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Rummler |first1=Orion |title="I want to choose flight": Families look to leave states banning health care for trans kids |url=https://www.axios.com/2021/05/01/families-leave-states-banning-health-care-trans-kids |work=[[Axios (website)|Axios]] |date=May 1, 2021 |access-date=July 22, 2023 |archive-date=July 22, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230722060858/https://www.axios.com/2021/05/01/families-leave-states-banning-health-care-trans-kids |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Colombini |first1=Stephanie |title=Families of trans youth weigh leaving Florida as more bans on gender-affirming care loom |url=https://wusfnews.wusf.usf.edu/health-news-florida/2023-04-07/families-trans-youth-weigh-leaving-florida-bans-gender-affirming-care |work=[[WUSF (FM)|WUSF]] |date=April 7, 2023 |access-date=July 22, 2023 |archive-date=July 22, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230722060859/https://wusfnews.wusf.usf.edu/health-news-florida/2023-04-07/families-trans-youth-weigh-leaving-florida-bans-gender-affirming-care |url-status=live }}</ref>
Several states passed legislation preventing trans people and their families, as well as their healthcare providers relocating from other states, from being extradited. In 2022, Connecticut became the first state to implement such a law, alongside similar protections for reproductive healthcare providers and recipients.<ref>{{Cite act |type=House Bill |index=5506 |date=May 24, 2022 |article=Sec 484, 485, 486, 487, 488 |article-type= Section |legislature= The Connecticut General Assembly |page=681-686 |url=https://legiscan.com/CT/text/HB05506/2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220812193552/https://legiscan.com/CT/text/HB05506/2022 |archive-date=August 12, 2022}}</ref> Massachusetts, California, Illinois, Minnesota, New Jersey, Maryland, and Washington, D.C. have passed similar laws.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://thehill.com/changing-america/respect/equality/3579987-massachusetts-governor-signs-bill-safeguarding-reproductive-gender-affirming-health-care-into-law/ |title=Massachusetts governor signs bill safeguarding reproductive, gender-affirming health care into law |last1=Migdon |first1=Brooke |date=July 29, 2022 |access-date=July 16, 2023 |archive-date=April 6, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230406021447/https://thehill.com/changing-america/respect/equality/3579987-massachusetts-governor-signs-bill-safeguarding-reproductive-gender-affirming-health-care-into-law/ |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.wbur.org/news/2022/05/27/massachusetts-senate-roe-transgender-legal-protections |last1=Bebinger |first1=Martha |title=Mass. Senate moves to protect abortion providers from out-of-state court judgments and investigations |access-date=July 16, 2023 |archive-date=May 10, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230510181315/https://www.wbur.org/news/2022/05/27/massachusetts-senate-roe-transgender-legal-protections |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sacbee.com/news/politics-government/capitol-alert/article266601076.html |title=California to become sanctuary state for transgender children under new law |last1=Holden |first1=Lindsey |last2=Sheeler |first2=Andrew |access-date=July 16, 2023 |archive-date=September 30, 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220930143150/https://www.sacbee.com/news/politics-government/capitol-alert/article266601076.html |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite act |url=https://legiscan.com/DC/text/B24-0808/2021 |legislature=Washington DC Council |type=Council Bill |index=240808 |date=October 18, 2022}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Walz |first=Tim |author-link=Tim Walz |date=March 8, 2023 |title=Executive Order 23-03 |url=https://mn.gov/governor/assets/EO%2023-03%20Signed%20and%20filed_tcm1055-568332.pdf |url-status=live |access-date=March 23, 2023 |publisher=State of Minnesota Executive Department |archive-date=March 24, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230324011031/https://mn.gov/governor/assets/EO%2023-03%20Signed%20and%20filed_tcm1055-568332.pdf }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last1=Nieto-Munoz |first1=Sophie |date=April 4, 2023 |title=Governor Murphy declares N.J. 'safe haven' for transgender, nonbinary people |url=https://newjerseymonitor.com/briefs/governor-murphy-declares-n-j-safe-haven-for-transgender-nonbinary-people/ |access-date=2023-04-16 |website=New Jersey Monitor |language=en-US |archive-date=April 25, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230425094441/https://newjerseymonitor.com/briefs/governor-murphy-declares-n-j-safe-haven-for-transgender-nonbinary-people/ |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Murphy |first=Philip |author-link=Phil Murphy |date=April 4, 2023 |title=State of New Jersey Executive Order No. 326 |url=https://www.nj.gov/infobank/eo/056murphy/pdf/EO-326.pdf |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230413013500/https://www.nj.gov/infobank/eo/056murphy/pdf/EO-326.pdf |archive-date=April 13, 2023 |access-date=April 16, 2023}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |website=State of Maryland Executive Department |date=June 5, 2023 |title=State of Maryland Executive Order 01.01.2023.08 |url=https://governor.maryland.gov/Lists/ExecutiveOrders/Attachments/11/EO_01.01.2023.08_accessible.pdf |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230609174705/https://governor.maryland.gov/Lists/ExecutiveOrders/Attachments/11/EO_01.01.2023.08_accessible.pdf |archive-date=June 9, 2023 |access-date=June 9, 2023}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Migdon |first=Brooke |date=2023-06-08 |title=Maryland governor signs executive order protecting access to gender-affirming care |url=https://thehill.com/homenews/state-watch/4040993-maryland-governor-signs-executive-order-protecting-access-to-gender-affirming-care/ |access-date=2023-06-09 |website=The Hill |language=en-US |archive-date=June 14, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230614205309/https://thehill.com/homenews/state-watch/4040993-maryland-governor-signs-executive-order-protecting-access-to-gender-affirming-care/ |url-status=live }}</ref>
Some trans Americans have considered [[Transgender asylum seekers|claiming asylum]] in other countries, including European countries or Canada. However, some political analysts note that asylum applications will likely be denied, as no federal law exists restricting LGBT safety and because transgender individuals can likely move to a safer state in their own country.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Zoledziowski |first=Anya |date=2023-01-10 |title=Some Trans People Are Preparing to Flee the US and Seek Asylum Abroad |url=https://www.vice.com/en/article/dy7qnj/trans-people-fleeing-us-seek-asylum |access-date=2023-07-22 |website=Vice |language=en |archive-date=July 22, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230722192032/https://www.vice.com/en/article/dy7qnj/trans-people-fleeing-us-seek-asylum |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Hagen |first=Isobel van |title=Transphobia is on the rise in the US. Meet the transgender people planning to relocate to Europe because they can no longer stand the 'hostile environment.' |url=https://www.insider.com/nonprofit-trans-people-flee-the-us-onslaught-anti-lgbtq-legislation-2023-5 |access-date=2023-07-22 |website=Insider |language=en-US |archive-date=August 21, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230821070723/https://www.insider.com/nonprofit-trans-people-flee-the-us-onslaught-anti-lgbtq-legislation-2023-5 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |date=2023-01-10 |title=Trans People Are Fleeing the U.S. and Seeking Asylum As Politicians Target Them |url=https://jezebel.com/trans-people-are-seeking-asylum-from-the-u-s-as-politi-1849969852 |access-date=2023-07-22 |website=Jezebel |language=en |archive-date=July 22, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230722192032/https://jezebel.com/trans-people-are-seeking-asylum-from-the-u-s-as-politi-1849969852 |url-status=live }}</ref> Others worry that potential asylum applications could overwhelm immigration systems and prevent asylum access for those from more dangerous territory.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Logan |first=Nick |date=March 16, 2023 |title=This petition asks Canada to grant asylum to transgender people from the U.S. Could it work? |url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/us-transgender-asylum-petition-1.6779692 |access-date=July 22, 2023 |website=[[Canadian Broadcasting Corporation]] |archive-date=July 22, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230722192032/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/us-transgender-asylum-petition-1.6779692 |url-status=live }}</ref>
====Self-defense==== The increased targeting of LGBT people by right-wing militia groups such as the [[Proud Boys]] and the [[Oath Keepers]], led many LGBT people, particularly in conservative states such as Texas, to stockpile weapons and gear, including AR-15 rifles and modern body armor, while training to use them, often in groups.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/world/article-in-texas-members-of-lgbtq-community-arm-themselves-to-fight-right-wing/ |title=In Texas, members of LGBTQ community arm themselves to fight right-wing extremists |last=Vanderklippe |first=Nathan |work=The Globe and Mail |date=November 27, 2022 |access-date=July 18, 2023 |archive-date=June 3, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230603054221/https://www.theglobeandmail.com/world/article-in-texas-members-of-lgbtq-community-arm-themselves-to-fight-right-wing/ |url-status=live }}</ref>
====Travel warnings==== In May 2023, the [[Human Rights Campaign]] issued a [[travel warning|travel advisory]] for the state of [[Florida]], citing new laws targeting the LGBT community.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Migdon |first1=Brooke |title=Human Rights Campaign issues Florida travel advisory |url=https://thehill.com/homenews/lgbtq/4017783-human-rights-campaign-issues-florida-travel-advisory/ |website=The Hill |date=May 23, 2023 |access-date=8 September 2023}}</ref>
=== International === After a ten-day tour in which he met with State officials in Alabama, Florida, and California in August 2022, [[Victor Madrigal-Borloz]], a [[United Nations special rapporteur|United Nations Independent Expert]] on protection against violence and discrimination, warned about the erosion of LGBT rights in the United States.<ref name="UN expert">{{cite web |title=United States: UN expert warns LGBT rights being eroded, urges stronger safeguards |url=https://www.ohchr.org/en/press-releases/2022/08/united-states-un-expert-warns-lgbt-rights-being-eroded-urges-stronger |website=UN Human Rights Office of the High Commissioner |publisher=United Nations |access-date=June 15, 2023 |archive-date=October 11, 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221011182808/http://www.ohchr.org/en/press-releases/2022/08/united-states-un-expert-warns-lgbt-rights-being-eroded-urges-stronger |url-status=live }}</ref> Madrigal-Borloz stated, "I am deeply alarmed by a widespread, profoundly negative riptide created by deliberate actions to roll back the human rights of LGBT people at state level. The evidence shows that, without exception, these actions rely on prejudiced and stigmatising views of LGBT persons, in particular transgender children and youth, and seek to leverage their lives as props for political profit."<ref name="UN expert"/>
In August 2023, the [[Government of Canada]] issued a [[travel warning]] for LGBT visitors to the United States, advising citizens to check their destination's local laws before traveling.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Gillies |first1=Rob |title=Canada issues travel advisory warning LGBTQ+ community about U.S. laws that may affect them |url=https://www.pbs.org/newshour/world/canada-issues-travel-advisory-warning-lgbtq-community-about-u-s-laws-that-may-affect-them |website=PBS |date=August 31, 2023 |access-date=8 September 2023}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Austen |first1=Ian |title=Canada Cautions L.G.B.T.Q. Citizens Visiting U.S. Over State Laws |work=The New York Times |date=August 30, 2023 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2023/08/30/world/canada/travel-warning-us-lgbtq.html |access-date=8 September 2023}}</ref>
